HEADWORD: Paucity
<hw>Pau"ci*ty</hw> <pr>(p⟦add⟧"s⟦icr⟧*t⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[L. <ets>paucitas</ets>, fr. <ets>paucus</ets> few, little: cf. F.
<ets>paucit⟦eacute⟧</ets> See <er>Few</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Fewness; smallness of number; scarcity; rarity.</def>
<rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Revelation denies it by the stern reserve, the <qex>paucity</qex>,
and the incompleteness, of its communications.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Smallness of quantity; exiguity; insufficiency;
<as>as, <ex>paucity</ex> of blood</as>.</def> <rj><au>Sir T.
Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

